ancashire, England":"Lancashire, Anglie","Lowton, Winwick, Lancashire, England":"Winwick, Lancashire, Anglie"},"da":{"1480–":"1480–Afdød","1480–Female":"1480–Afdød","1500–1560":"1500–1560","1480–Male":"1480–Afdød","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1585":"1585","1571":"1571","1560":"1560","Abt 1500":"omkring 1500","1480":"1480","1549":"1549","Milgate, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Lowton, Winwick, Lancashire, England":"Winwick, Lancashire, England"},"nl":{"1480–":"1480–Overleden","1480–Female":"1480–Overleden","1500–1560":"1500–1560","1480–Male":"1480–Overleden","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1585":"1585","1571":"1571","1560":"1560","Abt 1500":"circa 1500","1480":"1480","1549":"1549","Milgate, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Lowton, Winwick, Lancashire, England":"Winwick, Lancashire, England"},"en":{"1480–":"1480–Deceased","1480–Female":"1480–Deceased","1500–1560":"1500–1560","1480–Male":"1480–Deceased","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1585":"1585","1571":"1571","1560":"1560","Abt 1500":"about 1500","1480":"1480","1549":"1549","Milgate, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Lowton, Winwick, Lancashire, England":"Winwick, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mather","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","occupational name for a mower or reaper of grass or hay, Old English <i>mǣthere</i>. Compare   Mead  ,   Mower  . Hay was formerly of great importance, not only as feed for animals in winter but also for bedding.","variant of   Mader  , reflecting an alternative pronunciation influenced by Old Norse <i>mathra</i> ‘madder (plant)’."],"variants":[{"name":"Mader","meanings":["English: variant of <b>Madder</b>, an occupational name for a dyer or seller of dye, from Middle English <i>mader</i>, <i>madour</i>, <i>mather</i>, shortened forms of Middle English <i>maderer</i>, <i>maderour</i>, <i>matherer</i> ‘seller of madder’ or ‘dyer who used madder’. <i>Mader</i> or <i>mather</i> (Old English <i>mædere</i>, Old Norse <i>mathra</i>) was the name for the plant <i>Rubia tinctorum</i>, used medicinally and for making red dye. It was also a word for red dye made from other sources. Compare   Mather  .","German and Swiss German (also <b>Mäder</b>), Dutch and French (Lorraine): occupational name for a reaper or mower, Middle High German <i>māder</i>, <i>mæder</i>, Middle Dutch <i>mader</i>. Compare   Moder  .","French: metonymic occupational name for a carpenter, from Occitan <i>madier</i> ‘beam’."]},{"name":"Mathers","meanings":["English: patronymic from   Mather  ."]},{"name":"Mead","meanings":["English:","topographic name for someone who lived by a meadow, from Middle English <i>mede</i> ‘meadow’ (Old English <i>mǣd</i>), or a habitational name from one or more of the many places so named, such as Meads in Harford (Devon).","perhaps from Middle English <i>mede</i> ‘mead, alcoholic drink of fermented honey and water’, possibly denoting one who was fond of the drink or who made or sold mead. Compare   Meader  ."]}]},{"name":"Humphry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Humfrey","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."]},{"name":"Humfry","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":69,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705202,"age":78,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705206,"age":91,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705207,"age":105,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Humphry Mather was born in 1480, in Lancashire, England. He married Alice Scott about 1500. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"1480–":"1480–Surnud","1480–Female":"1480–Surnud","1500–1560":"1500–1560","1480–Male":"1480–Surnud","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1585":"1585","1571":"1571","1560":"1560","Abt 1500":"umbes 1500","1480":"1480","1549":"1549","Milgate, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Lowton, Winwick, Lancashire, England":"Winwick, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"1480–":"1480–Kuollut","1480–Female":"1480–Kuollut","1500–1560":"1500–1560","1480–Male":"1480–Kuollut","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1585":"1585","1571":"1571","1560":"1560","Abt 1500":"noin 1500","1480":"1480","1549":"1549","Milgate, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Lowton, Winwick, Lancashire, England":"Winwick, Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"1480–":"1480–Décédé","1480–Female":"1480–Décédée","1500–1560":"1500–1560","1480–Male":"1480–Décédé","1558":